    <h3>8.1 Tor, VPN & Proxy Users</h3>
    <div class="warning">
        <p><strong>🧅 Important notice for Tor Browser, VPN, and proxy users:</strong></p>
        <p>WetWijzer is designed for <strong>EU-based users</strong>. If your connection appears to originate from <strong>outside the EU</strong>, you will be asked to complete a one-time security challenge (<a href="/privacy-policy#section-10-3">ALTCHA proof-of-work</a>) before accessing the platform.</p>
    </div>
    <p>This affects you if you use:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Tor Browser:</strong> Tor exit nodes are almost always located outside the EU (commonly in the US, Canada, or Asia). Our server sees the exit node's IP address, not yours - which means it looks like a non-EU visit.</li>
        <li><strong>VPN services:</strong> If your VPN exit server is located outside the EU/EEA/Switzerland/UK, you will trigger the same geo-security check.</li>
        <li><strong>Corporate proxies:</strong> Some corporate proxy chains route traffic through non-EU gateways.</li>
    </ul>
    <h4>What this means in practice:</h4>
    <table>
        <tr>
            <th>Scenario</th>
            <th>Geo-Check?</th>
            <th>Can You Use the Chatbot?</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Regular browser, EU IP address</td>
            <td>❌ No check needed</td>
            <td>✅ Yes, immediately</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>VPN with EU exit (e.g. Netherlands, Germany)</td>
            <td>❌ No check needed</td>
            <td>✅ Yes</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>VPN with non-EU exit (e.g. US, Singapore)</td>
            <td>✅ One-time ALTCHA challenge</td>
            <td>✅ Yes, after verification</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Tor Browser (random exit node)</td>
            <td>✅ ALTCHA challenge (likely)</td>
            <td>✅ Yes, after verification</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
    <div class="legal-notice">
        <p><strong>Privacy note for Tor users:</strong> We respect your right to browse anonymously. The geo-security check does not de-anonymize you - it only verifies you are human through a proof-of-work challenge that runs entirely on our own server. No data is sent to third parties. However, be aware that when using Tor, your traffic exits through a <strong>third-party relay node</strong> that you do not control. While TLS encryption protects the content of your chatbot questions from the exit node operator, the exit node can see which website you are visiting (wetwijzer.be). This is a property of Tor itself, not of our platform.</p>
    </div>
    <p><strong>Recommendation:</strong> If you use a VPN for privacy and want to avoid the geo-check entirely, select an <strong>EU-based exit server</strong> (e.g. Netherlands, Germany, France, Sweden). This also ensures your connection to our server stays within the EU network backbone.</p>

